Weekly backlog burndown: in the ~10 hours before the account's weekly Codex (ChatGPT plan) usage reset, spend the remaining credits implementing backlog items across The Borg. The job fires twice (Fri 21:09 and Sat 02:19) because Codex's rolling 5-hour session limit caps what one run can burn: the first run typically dies at the session limit, and the second starts with a fresh session window and resumes the same plan.

This job runs headless via `codex exec` from `${BORG_ROOT}/c4po` with the workspace root added as a writable working directory (see `.bin/run-scheduled-task.sh`). It is EXPECTED to die mid-run when credits run out — every phase therefore leaves durable state (commits, checked boxes) before moving on, and the plan email goes out before implementation starts.

The phases below are named, not numbered, so the paired `/backlog-burndown` command can reference them without breaking when this file is edited.

GATE — decide the run mode: FRESH, RESUME, or stop.
Determine the current ISO week with `date +%G-W%V` and read `${BORG_ROOT}/c4po/.claude/scheduled/state/c4po-backlog-burndown.json` (if present).
- State file missing, or its `week` field is not the current ISO week → **FRESH**: run every phase below.
- `week` equals the current ISO week and the plan file (`${BORG_ROOT}/c4po/.claude/scheduled/state/c4po-backlog-burndown-plan.md`) still has unchecked actionable items → **RESUME**: skip PRIORITIZE, CONSOLIDATE, NOTIFY PLAN, and RECORD STATE; go straight to BURN at the first unchecked item. A prior run this week already planned, emailed, and recorded state — this run only continues the burn.
- `week` equals the current ISO week and the plan has no unchecked actionable items (or the plan file is missing) → stop and output nothing; the week's plan is spent.

WINDOW — abort if fired outside the pre-reset window.
The account's weekly Codex usage reset is **Saturday 7:09 AM local** (from `/status` in Codex); launchd fires this job Friday 21:09 and again Saturday 02:19 (a few minutes past the first run's 5-hour session-limit boundary). The valid window spans midnight: if the current local time is not (Friday at or after 20:40) and not (Saturday before 06:40), stop and output nothing (launchd fires missed events on wake, so a sleeping Mac can delay a run) — running after the reset would burn the fresh week's budget, which defeats the purpose. If the account's reset time ever changes, update this paragraph and the `weekly-fri-21-09-sat-02-19` schedule in `.bin/install-scheduled-tasks.sh` together.

PRIORITIZE — reorder every backlog in place.
Enumerate the backlogs: `${BORG_ROOT}/BACKLOG.md` (workspace) and every `${BORG_ROOT}/repos/*/BACKLOG.md` (check the filesystem — `repos/` is git-ignored, so its children never appear in workspace git status). Reorder each file's open items by priority, preserving that file's own format and conventions (the workspace file is a flat checkbox list — reorder it highest-priority-first; a repo file with priority tiers keeps its tiers, moving items between tiers only when clearly warranted). Priority rubric: user pain in active use > bugs > security/correctness > features > nice-to-haves; weigh what unblocks other items. Do not rewrite item content. Commit each reordered file in its own repo (workspace file in the theborg repo, repo files in their repos).

CONSOLIDATE — build the run plan.
Write `${BORG_ROOT}/c4po/.claude/scheduled/state/c4po-backlog-burndown-plan.md` (overwriting any previous run's plan): a single prioritized union of all open items across every backlog, one checkbox line per item with its source file, owning agent/repo, and dispatch directory (per BURN). Items a headless run cannot do get a `needs-user:` marker with a one-line reason instead of a checkbox — anything requiring a physical device, user-only verification, credentials or purchases, app-store/publishing actions, or a destructive/irreversible operation. Order the actionable rest by the same priority rubric.

NOTIFY PLAN — email the plan before burning.
Pipe the plan into `${BORG_ROOT}/.bin/notify-email.sh c4po "Borg backlog burndown — {YYYY-MM-DD} — plan: {N} item(s), {K} needs-user"` (reads the message from stdin). Body header: same as the subject. This email is sent BEFORE implementation because the run is expected to die when credits run out; it is the user's record of what the run set out to do.

RECORD STATE — mark the week done before burning.
Write `${BORG_ROOT}/c4po/.claude/scheduled/state/c4po-backlog-burndown.json` with `{"week":"YYYY-Www","date":"YYYY-MM-DD","ts":"<ISO 8601 timestamp>","planned":<N>,"needs_user":<K>}`. `mkdir -p` the state directory first if needed. State is recorded now, not at the end, because the end may never arrive.

BURN — implement items until credits run out.
Loop over the plan top-down, dispatching each item to a FRESH headless child session — one `codex exec` per item. This keeps any item from paying for the context accumulated by the ones before it (context rot and token cost both grow with session length), and it loads the correct AGENTS.md chain for the item's owner. This session is the orchestrator only: it spawns children, verifies evidence, and updates trackers — it does not implement items itself.
- Dispatch directory: workspace item owned by an agent → `${BORG_ROOT}/<agent>`; owned by the workspace itself → `${BORG_ROOT}`; repo item → that repo's root under `${BORG_ROOT}/repos/`.
- Spawn: from the dispatch directory, run `codex exec --sandbox workspace-write "<child prompt>"`; for workspace items also pass `--add-dir "${BORG_ROOT}"` (an agent-owned item may touch files outside its agent dir). Pass no `-m` or effort overrides — model and reasoning effort come from `~/.codex/config.toml` defaults. No MCP flags are needed: codex loads MCP servers only from `~/.codex/config.toml`, which has no telegram server, so the poller-clobbering hazard that made Claude runs pass `--strict-mcp-config` does not apply.
- The child prompt must be self-contained: the item's full text, its source BACKLOG.md path, and the standing rules — implement in the owning repo following its AGENTS.md, rules, and ADR conventions; verify as far as headless allows (run the repo's tests/build if it has them; never claim verification the item reserves for a device or the user); commit with a clear message; never push to any remote; never write `cerebruh/` wiki content (read-only for all agents per the workspace AGENTS.md — codex does not enforce Claude's deny rules, so state this rule in every child prompt); do NOT edit any BACKLOG.md or the plan file (the parent owns trackers); if the item proves infeasible headless, commit nothing and print `INFEASIBLE: <reason>`.
- Verify by evidence, not the child's self-report: check the dispatch repo's `git log` for the item's commit(s), and `git status` for stray uncommitted changes (commit them if they complete the item's work, otherwise revert them).
- Update trackers in the parent: check the item off (or move it to a Done section, per that file's convention) in its source BACKLOG.md and in the plan file; commit the tracker updates. If the child reported infeasible or left no commit, mark the item `skipped: <reason>` in the plan file instead and move on.
Continue until no actionable items remain — or the run dies with the credits, which is the expected exit; the commits and checked boxes are the durable record.

WRAP — only reached if the plan empties before the credits do.
Pipe a summary (items completed / skipped / needs-user, with commit hashes) into `${BORG_ROOT}/.bin/notify-email.sh c4po "Borg backlog burndown — {YYYY-MM-DD} — {C} done, {S} skipped"`. Body header: same as the subject.
